NibblesPG

Target IP: 192.168.209.47

Scanning



There are four TCP ports open on the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed for this application. Performing a directory search with multiple wordlists did not result in anything useful.

Port 5437: PostgreSQL

I used the auxiliary module scanner/postgres/postgres_login from Metasploit to perform a login brutesearch.The options I set are shown above.


Performing a bruteforce for username and password was useful as I found a valid username and password. The credential postgres:postgres works against the target machine.

Exploitation


I used the exploit module multi/postgres/postgres_copy_from_program_cmd_exec to gain a reverse shell connection on port 80 on my machine.


This module worked and now I have a reverse shell connection. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running find / -perm -u=s 2>/dev/null shows the binary /usr/bin/find has a SUID bit set.


And now I have a root shell.
